d bondage today—from unlawful detention to sex trafficking to the refugee crisis to genocide—we must turn to contemporary literature, which reveals how the literary forms used to tell these stories derive from the antebellum genre of the slave narrative. Exploring the ethics and aesthetics of globalism, the book presents alternative conceptions of human rights, showing that the revival and proliferation of slave narratives offers not just an occasion to revisit the Atlantic past, but also for re-narrating the global present. In reassessing these legacies and their ongoing relation to race and the human, Runaway Genres creates a new map with which to navigate contemporary black diaspora literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAfrican diaspora. 0aGlobalizationxSocial aspectszAfricaxHistory. 0aSlavery in literature. 0aSlaveryxHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / African-American.2bisacsh  aAfrican American.  aAfrican.  aAfropolitan.  aAhmadou Kourouma.  aAtlantic.  aCaryl Phillips.  aChimamanda Adichie.  aChris Abani.  aColson Whitehead.  aDave Eggers.  aDinaw Mengestu.  aFrancis Bok.  aFrederick Douglass.  aGlobal South.  aIshmael Beah.  aMat Johnson.  aNoViolet Bulawayo.  aOthello.  aPaul Beatty.  aSusan Minot.  aTeju Cole.  aToni Morrison.  aUnderground Railroad.  aabolition.  aabsurd.  aaffect.  aanalogy.  ablack Atlantic.  ablackness.  achild soldier.  adiaspora.  afiction and slavery.  agothic.  ahuman rights.  ahuman trafficking.  ahumanitarianism.  aimmigrant.  aintertextuality.  amemoir.  amodern slavery.  aneo-slave narrative.  aneoliberal.  apost-blackness.  apostcolonial.  arefugees.  asatire.  asentimentalism.  aslave narrative.  atrauma.  aventriloquism.  awar.08iTitle is part of eBoo